---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Portfolio | lisAIconsulting">

  <section class="page-intro">
    <p class="eyebrow">Portfolio</p>
    <h1>Selected Work</h1>
    <p class="intro">
      This page highlights practical examples of delivery, automation, and structured execution.
      The focus is on showing how operational problems can be translated into working solutions
      that improve visibility, consistency, and follow-through.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="portfolio-item">
    <div class="portfolio-header">
      <div>
        <p class="item-label">Featured Example</p>
        <h2>Defect Tracking Automation (n8n)</h2>
      </div>
      <span class="tag">Workflow Automation</span>
    </div>

    <p class="item-summary">
      This example demonstrates how a common operational problem—unstructured defect intake and inconsistent tracking—
      can be improved through lightweight automation, clearer process flow, and centralized visibility.
    </p>

    <div class="summary-grid">
      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Problem</h3>
        <p>
          Teams often capture defects through scattered channels such as email, chat, or informal notes.
          That creates inconsistent intake, incomplete information, and limited visibility into what has
          been reported, reviewed, or resolved.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Solution</h3>
        <p>
          I built an automated defect intake and tracking workflow using n8n, with structured submission,
          standardized handling, and centralized logging into Google Sheets. The design focuses on making
          issue reporting more consistent while reducing manual coordination effort.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="info-card">
        <h3>Outcome</h3>
        <p>
          The result is a cleaner, more traceable process that improves visibility, supports follow-through,
          and gives teams a lightweight way to move from ad hoc reporting to a more structured operating model.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="two-column">
      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>Business Context</h3>
        <p>
          Defect management breaks down quickly when intake is informal and tracking is inconsistent.
          Even simple workflows benefit from structure: a clear point of entry, standardized fields,
          and a shared location for review and follow-up.
        </p>
        <p>
          This example was created to demonstrate that practical process improvement does not always require
          a large platform implementation. In many cases, the right combination of workflow logic, intake
          design, and centralized tracking can significantly improve operational discipline.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <h3>What This Demonstrates</h3>
        <ul class="clean-list">
          <li>Translation of an operational problem into a working solution</li>
          <li>Workflow automation design using lightweight tooling</li>
          <li>Improved intake structure and centralized visibility</li>
          <li>Connection between business need, process flow, and output</li>
          <li>Ability to package technical work into a client-facing artifact</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Workflow Overview</h3>
      <p>
        The workflow starts with defect submission through a structured form, triggers automated handling in n8n,
        and records the issue in a centralized tracking sheet. This creates a more reliable intake path and a
        shared source of truth for review and follow-up.
      </p>

      <div class="workflow-box">
        <div class="workflow-step">User submits defect form</div>
        <div class="workflow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="workflow-step">n8n workflow triggered</div>
        <div class="workflow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="workflow-step">Submission data validated and formatted</div>
        <div class="workflow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="workflow-step">Defect logged to centralized tracker</div>
        <div class="workflow-arrow">↓</div>
        <div class="workflow-step">Team visibility and follow-up</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Sample Screens</h3>
      <p>
        The screenshots below show the working flow, intake structure, and tracking output used to support
        a more consistent defect management process.
      </p>

      <div class="image-grid">
        <figure class="image-card">
          <img src="/images/portfolio/workflow.png" alt="n8n defect tracking workflow" />
          <figcaption>n8n workflow automation</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="image-card">
          <img src="/images/portfolio/form.png" alt="Structured defect intake form" />
          <figcaption>Structured defect intake form</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="image-card">
          <img src="/images/portfolio/sheet.png" alt="Centralized defect tracking output" />
          <figcaption>Centralized tracking output</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-section">
    <h2>Interested in Similar Work?</h2>
    <p>
      lisAIconsulting supports organizations that need practical help with AI programs,
      workflow improvement, automation opportunities, and delivery execution.
    </p>
    <a class="button" href="/contact">Contact Me</a>
  </section>
  <style>
    .container {
      max-width: 900px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 2rem 1rem;
    }

    h1 {
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }

    p {
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
      color: #555;
    }

    .image-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
      gap: 1.5rem;
    }

    .image-card {
      border: 1px solid #eee;
      border-radius: 10px;
      overflow: hidden;
      background: #fff;
      box-shadow: 0 2px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
      transition: transform 0.2s ease, box-shadow 0.2s ease;
    }

    .image-card:hover {
      transform: translateY(-4px);
      box-shadow: 0 8px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.08);
    }

    .image-card img {
      width: 100%;
      display: block;
    }

    .image-card figcaption {
      padding: 0.75rem;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      color: #333;
      text-align: center;
    }
  </style>

</Layout>
